The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | The City Diary
                                                                                                               The City Diary
                The body of a 68-year-old man was found in the bathroom of his first-floor flat in Dum Dum Park on Monday afternoon. According to local residents, the flat was closed for the past two days and a foul smell was emanating from it. Police said Pradumnya Roy, a widower, lived alone. Cops suspect Roy suffered a cardiac arrest. The body has been sent for post-mortem.     An 18-year-old pillion rider died on Monday morning after being injured in a motorcycle accident on the Vidyasagar Setu on Sunday night. Police said Saurav Mukherjee, a resident of Laksman Das Lane in Howrah, was heading home when the bike skidded on the bridge. He was taken to SSKM Hospital where he died. The other person on the bike escaped with minor injuries.     A 26-year-old man was critically injured on Sunday night while making crude bombs with three others when one of the bombs accidentally exploded. Saumya Patra was making the bombs in an abandoned pump house in Nepal Saha Lane in Howrah, police said. Residents rushed to the spot on hearing the explosion and found Patra bleeding profusely from his right hand. The others had fled. Patra was arrested and admitted to Medical College and Hospital.    Namita Das, 60, was found hanging in her Cossipore Road home on Monday evening. Police said Das, who was suffering from multiple diseases, had an altercation with her son Debojit and his wife on Monday morning. In the evening, when Debojit and his wife and children were going out, they found Das hanging.     Antoni Bayes-Genis, a cardiologist from Spain, met cardiologists in the city to spread awareness about a cost-effective and accurate method to diagnose heart failure  testing NT-proBNP levels in the blood. Testing the levels of the heart enzyme, secreted when the heart muscle is over-stretched, will lead to diagnosis of heart failure even among patients without symptoms.     A woman who had left a bag containing documents and a cellphone on a private bus on Monday got it back with the help of the bus conductor. Mimi Sil of Baranagar boarded the bus plying on route 34 B at Dunlop but left behind her bag when she got off at Chiriamore. She went to Cossipore police station, where officers dialled her number and a conductor who had spotted the bag on the seat took the call. He later handed over the bag to the cops in Dunlop.    Five cops of the Radio Flying Squad sustained injuries after the vehicle they were travelling in collided with a truck on the Shakespeare Sarani-Loudon Street crossing on Monday.                                                                                                                                                                   
